              <h2 id=3D"what-is-a-t-test"><strong>What is a <em>t-</em>test=
?</strong></h2>
              <p>A <em>t</em>-test (also known as Student's <em>t</em>-test=
) is a tool for evaluating <a href=3D"https://www.jmp.com/en/statistics-kno=
wledge-portal/measures-of-central-tendency-and-variability/mean-median-and-=
mode" title=3D"the means">the means</a> of one or two populations using hyp=
othesis testing. A t-test may be used to evaluate whether a single group di=
ffers from a known value (<a href=3D"https://www.jmp.com/en/statistics-know=
ledge-portal/t-test/one-sample-t-test" title=3D"a one-sample t-test">a one-=
sample t-test</a>), whether two groups differ from each other (<a href=3D"h=
ttps://www.jmp.com/en/statistics-knowledge-portal/t-test/two-sample-t-test"=
 title=3D"an independent two-sample t-test">an independent two-sample t-tes=
t</a>), or whether there is a significant difference in paired measurements=
 (<a href=3D"https://www.jmp.com/en/statistics-knowledge-portal/t-test/pair=
ed-t-test" title=3D"a paired, or dependent samples t-test">a paired, or dep=
endent samples t-test</a>).</p>
              <h2 id=3D"how-are-t-tests-used"><strong>How are <em>t</em>-te=
sts used?</strong></h2>
              <p>First, you define the hypothesis you are going to test and=
 specify an acceptable risk of drawing a faulty conclusion. For example, wh=
en comparing two populations, you might hypothesize that their means are th=
e same, and you decide on an acceptable probability of concluding that a di=
fference exists when that is not true. Next, you calculate a test statistic=
 from your data and compare it to a theoretical value from a&nbsp; <em>t-</=
em> distribution. Depending on the outcome, you either reject or fail to re=
ject your null hypothesis.</p>
              <h2 id=3D"what-if-i-have-more-than-two-groups"><strong>What i=
f I have more than two groups?</strong></h2>
              <p>You cannot use a <em>t</em>-test. Use a multiple compariso=
n method. Examples are analysis of variance (<a href=3D"https://www.jmp.com=
/en/statistics-knowledge-portal/one-way-anova" title=3D"ANOVA">ANOVA</a>), =
Tukey-Kramer pairwise comparison, Dunnett's comparison to a control, and an=
alysis of means (ANOM).</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div></div><div class=3D"default-content-wrapper"><h2 id=3D"t-test=
-assumptions"><em>t</em>-Test assumptions</h2><p>While <em>t</em>-tests are=
 relatively robust to deviations from assumptions, <em>t</em>-tests do assu=
me that:</p><ul>
          <li>The data are continuous.</li>
          <li>The sample data have been randomly sampled from a population.=
</li>
          <li>There is homogeneity of variance (i.e., the variability of th=
e data in each group is similar).</li>
          <li>The distribution is approximately normal.</li>
        </ul><p>For two-sample <em>t</em>-tests, we must have independent s=
amples. If the samples are not independent, then a paired <em>t</em>-test m=
ay be appropriate.</p><h2 id=3D"types-of-t-tests">Types of <em>t</em>-tests=
